erning visions as to prophecy -- tThe rebellion is now a thing of the past, it is now a page -- tCrowfoot chief of the Blackfoot, like a dark Duke of Wellington, in the house of the ‘white chief with one eye open,’ as they called Jingo (from his watchfulness and his eyeglass) -- tEndnotes -- tLiterary Sources -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMerging poetry and historical records, Zits masterfully (re)creates a poetic view of the Frog Lake Massacre of April 2, 1885. His collage and cut-up techniques challenge the histories penned by the event’s recorders and reflect upon the difficult and painful complexities of past and present. He weaves together voices of Métis and First Nations participants, settlers, and military officials, using tape transcripts, historical accounts, memoirs, and footnotes to create a unique, non-narrative historiography of fragmented poetic language. This innovative work of literary montage digs deep into a historic period that continues to garner scholarly and public interest. Readers interested in poetry and Canadian history will find this an intriguing new collection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxHistoryvPoetry. 0aFrog Lake Massacre, Frog Lake, Alta., 1885vPoetry. 0aFrog Lake Massacre, Frog Lake, Alta., 1885xHistoriographyvPoetry. 0aMontage. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aCanadian Literature.  aHistoriography.  aPoetry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088864819840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780888648198423Coveruh